      "tags": ["pronouns","grammar","b1"],
      "markdown": "# üéØ B7 ‚Äî Object Pronouns: lo/la/los/las, le/les ‚Üí se (B1)\n\n**Goal:** Use direct and indirect object pronouns together, and apply the **le/les ‚Üí se** rule.\n\n---\n\n## üß© Direct vs Indirect Objects\n\n| Type         | Meaning | Pronouns                  | Example                     |\n|--------------|-----------|-------------------|------------------------------|\n| Direct (DO)  | receives action | lo, la, los, las       | *Veo el libro ‚Üí Lo veo* |\n| Indirect (IO)| benefits from action | le, les                 | *Doy el libro a Juan ‚Üí Le doy el libro* |\n\n---\n\n## ‚ö° Double Object Rule\n- **Order:** IO + DO ‚Üí *Le doy el libro ‚Üí Le lo doy ‚ùå*\n- **BUT:** **le/les become se** before lo/la/los/las\n- ‚úÖ *Se lo doy.* (I give it to him)\n\n> üí° Always put pronouns **before the verb** (or attached to infinitives/gerunds)\n\n---\n\n## üñº Flowchart (mental map)\n\n```\nStart\n ‚îî‚îÄ Is there an indirect object? ‚Üí yes ‚Üí use me/te/le/nos/os/les\n ‚îî‚îÄ Is there a direct object? ‚Üí yes ‚Üí use lo/la/los/las\n     ‚îî‚îÄ If both used:\n         ‚îî‚îÄ le/les + lo/la/los/las ‚Üí se + lo/la/los/las\n         ‚îî‚îÄ Order: IO + DO ‚Üí Se lo doy\n```\n\n**Example:**\n- *Doy el libro a Juan* ‚Üí *Se lo doy.*\n- *Env√≠a las cartas a Mar√≠a* ‚Üí *Se las env√≠a.*\n\n---\n\n> üìù Summary: IO (le/les) + DO (lo/la/los/las) ‚Üí se + lo/la/los/las\n",
      "references": []
    }
